(188, 1, '2020-09-14 06:53:55', '2020-09-14 06:53:55', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Municipal Planning Development Office through the Municipal Planning Team conducted an actual land use survey in accordance with the guidelines prepared by the Housing and Land Use Regulatory Board. The aim was to be able to reflect the existing land uses and development patterns in the municipality.&nbsp; The various land uses and development patterns were observed, reflected in the existing land use maps (See Map Nos. 1 and 2) and quantified and tabulated in the succeeding sections.&nbsp; They are used extensively in the formulation and development of a package of intervention policies and strategies designed to achieve the desired spatial development arrangement, which in the perspective of the planning team shall provide the best opportunities accorded to the municipality for economic development.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>1. <u>EXISTING URBAN LAND USES</u></strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul style=\"list-style-type:none;\"><li><strong><em>1.1. Existing Functional Land Uses in the Urban Area</em></strong><br><br><p>The sole urban area of Burgos is the Poblacion which covers 143.6391 hectares housing a population of 2,524 people in 679 households in 2010. The population density in the urban area is quite high at 19 persons per hectare (See Table 1 and Figure 1).</p>\n<ul style=\"list-style-type:none;\"><li><strong><em>1.1.1. Residential Use</em></strong><br><br><p>The existing residential area in the urban areas is approximately 35.0900 hectares which accounts for 24.43% of the land use in the urban area (see Table 1and Figure 1, below).The residential areas are made up of blocks bounded by municipal roads. They are also clustered in ribbon-like morphology along municipal thoroughfares.&nbsp; Most of the houses are single-detached dwelling units and are made of mixed construction materials. Supplementing these residential areas are privately-owned subdivisions going up to a total of 4.3596 hectares.</p></li><li><strong><em>1.1.2. Commercial Use</em></strong><br><br><p>Practically all commercial and trading activities in the urban area take place in the 2.4764 hectares occupied by the various existing commercial establishments of the municipality including the public market. The existing public market is complemented by a number of barangay convenience stores, retail outlets,a mini-grocery, rice stalls, some eateries, medical and dental clinics, pharmacies, and other commercial establishments providing goods and services to the populace.</p></li><li><strong><em>1.1.3. Institutional Use</em></strong><br><br><p>Covering approximately an aggregate of 14.4200 hectares (9.91% of the urban area), lands used for institutional purposes include the municipal compound occupied by the Municipal Hall and its appurtenances, the barangay health center and offices of other government agencies. In this classification are also the barangay hall and other public and private offices. A large bulk of the institutional land use in the urban area is accounted for by the different educational institutions. Also included here are church buildings of various religious denominations. Around the urban area are open spaces classified as park and recreation areas going up to 0.5266 hectares which are included in this accounting.</p>\n</li><li><strong><em>1.1.4. Industrial Use</em></strong><br><br><p>There are still scattered areas actually used for industrial purposes found in the Poblacion area.&nbsp; This has particular reference to woodcrafts, ironworks, rice mills, auto shops and other processing centers.&nbsp; These establishments cover an aggregate area of around 0.0800 hectares of the total urban land area accounting for only 0.05% of the urban area.</p></li>\n<li><strong><em>1.1.5. Agricultural Lands</em></strong><br><br><p>Agricultural lands comprise about 73.9024 hectares comprising a large 51.45% of the total urban area. Vacant lands are interspersed in the blocks and in the built-up areas, while the agricultural lands are generally situated at the outskirts of the urban barangay. There are agro-industrial establishments scattered in the urban area, consisting of swine and other animal farms which are counted under agricultural areas.</p></li><li><strong><em>1.1.6. Roads, Easements, Canals, Water Bodies</em></strong><br><br><p>Existing road rights-of-way cover, including the right-of-way occupied by easements and dikes cover an aggregate area of approximately 9.8900 hectares or 6.89% of the urban land. Water canals/bodies account for 0.9739 hectares.&nbsp;</p></li><li><strong><em>1.1.7. Special Uses</em></strong><br><br><p>Special land use is devoted for the cemetery in the Poblacion which covers around 1.2429 hectares used to provide for the general needs of the Municipality.<strong><br></strong></p></li>\n</ul>\n</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>2. <u>EXISTING GENERAL LAND USES</u></strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Burgos is noticeably an agricultural community. Its 14 barangays, including the Poblacion, occupies a total land area of 12,485.8528 hectares. It was inhabited by a total of 18,315 in 4,261 households in 2010 as per municipal demographic data, with a population density of about a person per hectare.&nbsp; The following were the observed land uses in the municipality(See Table 2 and Figure 2):</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul style=\"list-style-type:none;\"><li><strong><em>&nbsp;2.1. Functional Land Uses in the Rural Area</em></strong><br><br>\n<ul style=\"list-style-type:none;\"><li><strong><em>2.1.1. Built-up Areas</em></strong><br><br><p>The built-up area consists of the residential area made up of clustered dwelling units with the customary neighborhood, commercial facilities, institutional facilities, and other uses supportive to its activities.&nbsp; Found generally in clusters of ribbon-type accumulation, and in some cases ring-like development patterns, built-up areas outside of urban sites comprise approximately 90.5297 hectares. The total built-up area includes residential areas comprising 41.1900 hectares, subdivisions of 21.7901 hectares, as well as commercial areas covering0.0836hectares and institutional areas accounting for 27.4660 hectares.</p></li><li><strong><em>2.1.2. Agricultural and Agro-Industrial Areas, Pasture Land</em></strong><br><br><p>Most of the people in the municipality engage in farming.&nbsp; Of the total land area of the municipality, the land use survey revealed that large 26.25% or 3,277.1601 hectares are classified as agricultural lands. Rice being the staple food is the leading crop mainly planted in these lands.&nbsp; Commercial crops like corn and vegetables are also grown. Mangoes, banana and coconut are also produced intensively in the agricultural zone. These account for the agro-industrial areas covering 686.7595 hectares. The fishponds found only in Cacayasen extend only to a total of 1 hectare. Tracks of land used for the grazing of animals which are areas with fertile soil but are currently untapped for agricultural. The agricultural upland cover an area of 6.920.5044 hectares comprising around 55.427% of the municipal land area.</p></li><li><strong><em>2.1.3. Industrial Use</em></strong><br><br><p>Only a few industries are scattered around the municipality. Industrial establishments include woodcraft shops, bakeries, rice mills, welding and iron works, handicraft shops and food processing establishments. The industrial establishments of Burgos outside of the Poblacion go up to only 0.1730 hectares.</p></li>\n<li><strong><em>2.1.4 Forests</em></strong><br><br><p>Forest lands cover an area of 1,057.0000 hectares comprising 8.4% of the municipal land. Only 93.000 hectares of these are protected forests while 293.0000 hectares are classified production forests. The remaining hectares are unclassified forests.</p></li>\n<li><strong><em>2.1.5 Open Spaces</em></strong><br><br><p>Open spaces which are spaces used for parks and recreation, accounted for mainly by the sports areas and facilities in all the different barangays, go up to around 6.2000 hectares.</p></li>\n<li><strong><em>2.1.5 Tourism</em></strong><br><br><p>Identified tourism areas in Burgos go up to only 4.5000 hectares accounted for by the more or less developed areas in Caboangoan beach in Ilio-ilio and other identified sites. This is only 0.04%of the municipal land area.</p></li>\n<li><strong><em>2.1.6 Roads and Easements</em></strong><br><br><p>The total road network of the municipality (including easements and the dikes) has been determined to be about 133.1300 hectares or approximately 1.07% of the total municipal land area.&nbsp; Rural road to arable land ratio is less than kilometer per one hundred hectares.</p></li><li><strong><em>2.1.7 Water Bodies</em></strong><br><br><p>The rivers and the several smaller streams crisscrossing the municipality cover an area of around 160.5000 hectares or 1.29% of the total municipal land area. Swamps, ponds, irrigation canals, and other water bodies and other small farm reservoirs also provide irrigation water.</p></li><li><strong><em>2.1.8 Special Uses</em></strong><br><br><p>The purposes under this land use include the cemeteries covering 1.2625 hectares and the existing open garbage dumpsite making up 4.4945 hectares. Special land uses account for 0.46% of the municipal land area.</p></li><li><strong><em>2.1.9 Municipal Waters</em></strong><br><br><p>The coastal area of the municipality covers a total of 10,500 hectares located in the barangay of Ilio-Ilio which holds the whole coastline of Burgos. Coastal management in the municipality has relied on mixed usage of the waters of the municipality. Extending to 15 kilometers off the coast, fishing has been seen as a source of livelihood of the people through multiple fishing and aquaculture as well as for tourism activities.</p></li>\n</ul>\n</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->', 'Existing Land Use and Land Use Trends', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '70-revision-v1', '', '', '2020-09-14 06:53:55', '2020-09-14 06:53:55', '', 70, 'https://localhost/git/burgos-website/?p=188', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(189, 1, '2020-09-14 07:05:41', '2020-09-14 07:05:41', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The municipality has adopted the following goals, objectives and strategies:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>1.GOALS</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul style=\"list-style-type:none;\"><li><strong>1.1. Agriculture</strong>\n<ul><li>To supervise poverty alleviation and social equity</li><li>To intensify food production</li><li>To attain food sufficiency</li><li>To achieve rational use of agricultural resources</li><li>To achieve sustainable development</li><li>To support people empowerment</li></ul></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>1.2. Commerce and Industry</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>To increase municipal income through increased commercial and industrial activity</li><li>To expand commercial activity outside of the Poblacion</li><li>To minimize the municipal poverty rate through economic uplifting of the populace through commercial and industrial support</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>1.3. Infrastructure and Tourism</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>To improve the existing urban and rural roads of the municipality</li><li>To improve the farm to market roads in every barangay in order to spur economic development in the rural areas</li><li>To attain the safe and efficient movement of people, goods, services and information needed for municipal wide development</li><li>To provide the municipality with adequate and safe supply of water suitable for domestic consumption, water impounding and irrigation</li><li>To expand the Level II and construct a Level III Municipal Waterworks System</li><li>To energize the local economy through the modernization and expansion of the present water facilities</li><li>To provide the municipality’s population with adequate power supply to increase profitable economic activities and enhance productivity</li><li>To develop the tourism potential of the municipality using tourism as the common take off point for development of the other sectors of the municipality</li><li>To direct infrastructure development in support of tourism</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>1.4. Social Services</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>To provide quality education at all levels in order to enable everyone to be a skillful, productive, and self-reliant citizens</li><li>To enable the population of Burgos to achieve a level of health that will allow them to lead a socially and economically productive life with longer life expectancy, low infant mortality, low maternal mortality and less disability through measures that will guarantee each individual’s access to essential health care</li><li>To develop every individual, family and the less fortunate in Burgos into an effective contributor for the common welfare of the society and, consequently, toward progress for the municipality</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>2.OBJECTIVES</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>2.1. Agriculture&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>To attain self-sufficiency and food security in rice and other commodities</li><li>To increase farm production via integrated and diversified systems, improvement of irrigationfacilities and marketing support</li><li>To attain self-sufficiency and surplus in livestock and poultry production</li><li>To improve fishing practices in for municipal fishing and fishponds</li><li>To encourage farmers to engage in organic farming</li><li>To encourage farmers to raise vegetable and high value crops</li><li>To increase the productivity and income of marginal farmers</li><li>To ensure the productivity of agricultural resources over the long-term</li><li>To increase market access and develop seasonal markets</li><li>To increase access to modern agricultural technology and production schemes</li><li>To strengthen agro-based farmers’ cooperatives in terms of management and entrepreneurial capabilities</li><li>To establish an agro-industrial development assistance program</li><li>To strengthen the present technical capability and communication skills of DA and extension workers</li><li>To provide technical training on crop, livestock, and fish production</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>2.2. Commerce and Industry</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>To expand physical infrastructure for commerce and trade</li><li>To establish transport routes to municipal and provincial destinations to facilitate trade</li><li>To improve the quality of goods and services and the competitiveness of local resources</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>2.3. Infrastructure and Tourism</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>To widen and expand the existing road network and linkages</li><li>To improve the poor physical conditions of stretches of the provincial and barangay road, and to work for their proper maintenance by requesting concerned agencies for the regular allotment of funds, and the inclusion of said roads in the DPWH programs</li><li>To increase the safety factor for people and property on all roads in the municipality</li><li>To efficiently distribute potable water to the various barangays within the municipality</li><li>To improve water quality, and the reliability of water distribution</li><li>To reduce the incidence of water-borne diseases, and promote health and sanitation through the provision of safe water supply</li><li>To ensure that the goals of the National Electrification Program is properly implemented and achieved in the municipal and barangay levels</li><li>To efficiently distribute electrical power to the various barangays within the municipality</li><li>To improve and develop existing and potential tourist spots though the proper formulation of appropriate plans</li><li>To plan the connections between tourism and other sectors especially agriculture and commerce</li><li>To plan out and implement specific interventions in identified tourism potential areas</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>2.4. Social Services</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>To increase the literacy rate in the municipality</li><li>To increase the enrolment participation in all levels</li><li>To provide adequate classrooms for elementary and secondary schoolchildren</li><li>To provide and upgrade basic school facilities and equipment</li><li>To provide competent and well-trained teachers in all educational levels</li><li>To increase functional literacy through non-formal education</li><li>To achieve equality of opportunity in health status among all sectors of society</li><li>To address the specific health problems of the population,</li><li>To upgrade the status of and transform the health care delivery system</li><li>To promote active and sustained people’s participation in health care</li><li>To provide an integrated welfare package to the constituents on the basis of their needs and coordinate the service facilities</li><li>To care for, protect, and rehabilitate the socially disabled constituents and the physically and mentally handicapped</li><li>To be an advocate for policies and measures addressing social welfare concerns</li><li>To meet the MSWDO’s basic needs in carrying out its programs more effectively</li><li>To provide adequate and timely capital assistance for income generation</li><li>To provide livelihood opportunities</li><li>To reduce malnutrition cases in preschool children</li><li>To promote gender awareness and understanding of women issues and concerns</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>3.STRATEGIES</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>3.1. Agriculture</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>3.1.1. Crops</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Declare agricultural lands as SAFDZ areas</li><li>Planning for pasturelands and open spaces</li><li>Promotion of rice production technology using hybrid variety<strong></strong></li><li>Rehabilitation and maintenance of irrigation systems in irrigated barangays and expansion of irrigable areas<strong></strong></li><li>Construction of post-harvest facilities<strong></strong></li><li>Promotion of intensified and diversified rice based integrated farming system incorporating high value crops<strong></strong></li><li>Promotion of commercially viable and exportable crops <strong></strong></li><li>Implementation of production cost reduction technologies on rice, corn, and organic farming technology<strong></strong></li><li>Strengthening of cooperatives and farmers’ groups and organizations<strong></strong></li><li>Assisting of&nbsp; cooperatives who avail of loans from lending institutions <strong></strong></li><li>Establishment of techno-demo for identified crops adopting new technology<strong></strong></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>3.1.2. Livestock</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Promotion and dissemination of improved technology on livestock and poultry production</li><li>Encouraging of backyard poultry production</li><li>Upgrading of chicken breeds</li><li>Promotion on animal health care and disease management</li><li>Improvement of municipal slaughterhouse</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>3.1.3. Rural Infrastructure</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Provision of year-round irrigation to increase crop production</li><li>Provision of infrastructure support services (irrigation, farm-to-market roads, bridges, post-harvest facilities)<strong></strong></li><li>Promotion of information technology for wider access to agriculture and aquaculture information.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>3.1.4. Institutional Capability Building</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Strengthening of cooperatives, farmers’ organizations</li><li>Establish marketing with line agencies and credit linkages for loan<strong></strong></li><li>Provision of livelihood assistance to farmer beneficiaries through viable cooperative organizations</li><li>Provision of training on leadership, management, agribusiness, market and financial networking with private institutions</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>3.1.5. Marketing System and Agri-business Development</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Promotion of competitive agricultural products for domestic and international market demands</li><li>Conduct annual assessment and evaluation of agricultural performance to determine marketing demand of crops<strong></strong></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>3.1.6. Human Resource Development</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Upgrading of skills through training and other educational activities to enhance extension delivery activities</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>3.2. Commerce and Industry</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Develop the Poblacion and adjacent barangays as a growth area by being a central business district and introducing supply and support facilities in the aforementioned areas</li><li>Pave with concrete and/or asphalt roads in the potential commercial centers</li><li>Provide funds for the improvement of the existing public market and its annexes</li><li>Improve market and business tax collection and revenue raising schemes for reinvestment into commercial sector infrastructure</li><li>Provide entrepreneurial and business management training for local residents and set up trade fairs</li><li>&nbsp;</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>3.3. Infrastructure and Tourism</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Exercise vigilance and care in all major intersections and trunk lines in order to keep roads and passageways safe for both life and property.</li><li>Acquisition of water rights, and seeking professional consultations with the Local Water Utilities Authority on water resources management.</li><li>Upgrade and modernize the power supply distribution facilities in the municipality.</li><li>Monitor and /or maintain the performance of existing facilities.</li><li>Unite tourism plans agriculture and commercial plans</li><li>Revitalize beach tourism in coastal barangay</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>3.4. Social Services</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Elementary and secondary school facilities should be made accessible to all</li><li>Teacher training registration fees should be allocated from the Educational Support Fund (ESF)</li><li>Items for security guards especially for the National High Schools should be allocated from the ESF</li><li>The distribution of the ESF to public schools should be on a per capita basis and all school heads should be given the opportunity to identify their priority targets</li><li>Municipal government-owned lots used as school sites should be transferred to the Department of Education</li><li>Coordinate with the Technical Education and Skills Development Authority (TESDA) and the Commission on Higher Education (CHED) for the immediate establishment of such institutions</li><li>Promotion of Primary Health Care</li><li>Greater Emphasis on Promotive and Preventive Health Care</li><li>Strict Implementation of Existing Ordinances on Solid Waste Management</li><li>Increased Budgetary Allocation for the Purchase of Medicine and Medical Supplies</li><li>Sourcing of funding support for day care centers</li><li>Allocation of funds for livelihood and income generating projects</li><li>Intensification of the nutrition program thru massive supplemental feeding to malnourished children</li><li>Coordination with TESDA TLRC for skills development training for youth and&nbsp; mothers</li><li>Identification and listing of potential clients and community leaders</li><li>Activation and strengthening of existing organizations for disaster management and preparedness</li><li>Strengthening of the participation of NGOs to promote and implement programs through linkages and proper coordination</li><li>Training and mobilization of community volunteers and organization of the welfare structure</li><li>Putting up of Day Care Centers</li><li>Organization of an Out of School Youth (OSY) Groups</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->', 'GOALS, OBJECTIVES, STRATEGIES', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '106-revision-v1', '', '', '2020-09-14 07:05:41', '2020-09-14 07:05:41', '', 106, 'https://localhost/git/burgos-website/?p=189', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(190, 1, '2020-09-14 07:06:16', '2020-09-14 07:06:16', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The municipality has adopted the following goals, objectives and strategies:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>1.GOALS</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul style=\"list-style-type:none;\"><li><strong>1.1. Agriculture</strong><br><br>\n<ul><li>To supervise poverty alleviation and social equity</li><li>To intensify food production</li><li>To attain food sufficiency</li><li>To achieve rational use of agricultural resources</li><li>To achieve sustainable development</li><li>To support people empowerment</li></ul></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>1.2. Commerce and Industry</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>To increase municipal income through increased commercial and industrial activity</li><li>To expand commercial activity outside of the Poblacion</li><li>To minimize the municipal poverty rate through economic uplifting of the populace through commercial and industrial support</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>1.3. Infrastructure and Tourism</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>To improve the existing urban and rural roads of the municipality</li><li>To improve the farm to market roads in every barangay in order to spur economic development in the rural areas</li><li>To attain the safe and efficient movement of people, goods, services and information needed for municipal wide development</li><li>To provide the municipality with adequate and safe supply of water suitable for domestic consumption, water impounding and irrigation</li><li>To expand the Level II and construct a Level III Municipal Waterworks System</li><li>To energize the local economy through the modernization and expansion of the present water facilities</li><li>To provide the municipality’s population with adequate power supply to increase profitable economic activities and enhance productivity</li><li>To develop the tourism potential of the municipality using tourism as the common take off point for development of the other sectors of the municipality</li><li>To direct infrastructure development in support of tourism</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>1.4. Social Services</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>To provide quality education at all levels in order to enable everyone to be a skillful, productive, and self-reliant citizens</li><li>To enable the population of Burgos to achieve a level of health that will allow them to lead a socially and economically productive life with longer life expectancy, low infant mortality, low maternal mortality and less disability through measures that will guarantee each individual’s access to essential health care</li><li>To develop every individual, family and the less fortunate in Burgos into an effective contributor for the common welfare of the society and, consequently, toward progress for the municipality</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>2.OBJECTIVES</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>2.1. Agriculture&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>To attain self-sufficiency and food security in rice and other commodities</li><li>To increase farm production via integrated and diversified systems, improvement of irrigationfacilities and marketing support</li><li>To attain self-sufficiency and surplus in livestock and poultry production</li><li>To improve fishing practices in for municipal fishing and fishponds</li><li>To encourage farmers to engage in organic farming</li><li>To encourage farmers to raise vegetable and high value crops</li><li>To increase the productivity and income of marginal farmers</li><li>To ensure the productivity of agricultural resources over the long-term</li><li>To increase market access and develop seasonal markets</li><li>To increase access to modern agricultural technology and production schemes</li><li>To strengthen agro-based farmers’ cooperatives in terms of management and entrepreneurial capabilities</li><li>To establish an agro-industrial development assistance program</li><li>To strengthen the present technical capability and communication skills of DA and extension workers</li><li>To provide technical training on crop, livestock, and fish production</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>2.2. Commerce and Industry</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>To expand physical infrastructure for commerce and trade</li><li>To establish transport routes to municipal and provincial destinations to facilitate trade</li><li>To improve the quality of goods and services and the competitiveness of local resources</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>2.3. Infrastructure and Tourism</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>To widen and expand the existing road network and linkages</li><li>To improve the poor physical conditions of stretches of the provincial and barangay road, and to work for their proper maintenance by requesting concerned agencies for the regular allotment of funds, and the inclusion of said roads in the DPWH programs</li><li>To increase the safety factor for people and property on all roads in the municipality</li><li>To efficiently distribute potable water to the various barangays within the municipality</li><li>To improve water quality, and the reliability of water distribution</li><li>To reduce the incidence of water-borne diseases, and promote health and sanitation through the provision of safe water supply</li><li>To ensure that the goals of the National Electrification Program is properly implemented and achieved in the municipal and barangay levels</li><li>To efficiently distribute electrical power to the various barangays within the municipality</li><li>To improve and develop existing and potential tourist spots though the proper formulation of appropriate plans</li><li>To plan the connections between tourism and other sectors especially agriculture and commerce</li><li>To plan out and implement specific interventions in identified tourism potential areas</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>2.4. Social Services</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>To increase the literacy rate in the municipality</li><li>To increase the enrolment participation in all levels</li><li>To provide adequate classrooms for elementary and secondary schoolchildren</li><li>To provide and upgrade basic school facilities and equipment</li><li>To provide competent and well-trained teachers in all educational levels</li><li>To increase functional literacy through non-formal education</li><li>To achieve equality of opportunity in health status among all sectors of society</li><li>To address the specific health problems of the population,</li><li>To upgrade the status of and transform the health care delivery system</li><li>To promote active and sustained people’s participation in health care</li><li>To provide an integrated welfare package to the constituents on the basis of their needs and coordinate the service facilities</li><li>To care for, protect, and rehabilitate the socially disabled constituents and the physically and mentally handicapped</li><li>To be an advocate for policies and measures addressing social welfare concerns</li><li>To meet the MSWDO’s basic needs in carrying out its programs more effectively</li><li>To provide adequate and timely capital assistance for income generation</li><li>To provide livelihood opportunities</li><li>To reduce malnutrition cases in preschool children</li><li>To promote gender awareness and understanding of women issues and concerns</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>3.STRATEGIES</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>3.1. Agriculture</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>3.1.1. Crops</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Declare agricultural lands as SAFDZ areas</li><li>Planning for pasturelands and open spaces</li><li>Promotion of rice production technology using hybrid variety<strong></strong></li><li>Rehabilitation and maintenance of irrigation systems in irrigated barangays and expansion of irrigable areas<strong></strong></li><li>Construction of post-harvest facilities<strong></strong></li><li>Promotion of intensified and diversified rice based integrated farming system incorporating high value crops<strong></strong></li><li>Promotion of commercially viable and exportable crops <strong></strong></li><li>Implementation of production cost reduction technologies on rice, corn, and organic farming technology<strong></strong></li><li>Strengthening of cooperatives and farmers’ groups and organizations<strong></strong></li><li>Assisting of&nbsp; cooperatives who avail of loans from lending institutions <strong></strong></li><li>Establishment of techno-demo for identified crops adopting new technology<strong></strong></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>3.1.2. Livestock</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Promotion and dissemination of improved technology on livestock and poultry production</li><li>Encouraging of backyard poultry production</li><li>Upgrading of chicken breeds</li><li>Promotion on animal health care and disease management</li><li>Improvement of municipal slaughterhouse</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>3.1.3. Rural Infrastructure</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Provision of year-round irrigation to increase crop production</li><li>Provision of infrastructure support services (irrigation, farm-to-market roads, bridges, post-harvest facilities)<strong></strong></li><li>Promotion of information technology for wider access to agriculture and aquaculture information.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>3.1.4. Institutional Capability Building</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Strengthening of cooperatives, farmers’ organizations</li><li>Establish marketing with line agencies and credit linkages for loan<strong></strong></li><li>Provision of livelihood assistance to farmer beneficiaries through viable cooperative organizations</li><li>Provision of training on leadership, management, agribusiness, market and financial networking with private institutions</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>3.1.5. Marketing System and Agri-business Development</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Promotion of competitive agricultural products for domestic and international market demands</li><li>Conduct annual assessment and evaluation of agricultural performance to determine marketing demand of crops<strong></strong></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>3.1.6. Human Resource Development</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Upgrading of skills through training and other educational activities to enhance extension delivery activities</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>3.2. Commerce and Industry</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Develop the Poblacion and adjacent barangays as a growth area by being a central business district and introducing supply and support facilities in the aforementioned areas</li><li>Pave with concrete and/or asphalt roads in the potential commercial centers</li><li>Provide funds for the improvement of the existing public market and its annexes</li><li>Improve market and business tax collection and revenue raising schemes for reinvestment into commercial sector infrastructure</li><li>Provide entrepreneurial and business management training for local residents and set up trade fairs</li><li>&nbsp;</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>3.3. Infrastructure and Tourism</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Exercise vigilance and care in all major intersections and trunk lines in order to keep roads and passageways safe for both life and property.</li><li>Acquisition of water rights, and seeking professional consultations with the Local Water Utilities Authority on water resources management.</li><li>Upgrade and modernize the power supply distribution facilities in the municipality.</li><li>Monitor and /or maintain the performance of existing facilities.</li><li>Unite tourism plans agriculture and commercial plans</li><li>Revitalize beach tourism in coastal barangay</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>3.4. Social Services</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Elementary and secondary school facilities should be made accessible to all</li><li>Teacher training registration fees should be allocated from the Educational Support Fund (ESF)</li><li>Items for security guards especially for the National High Schools should be allocated from the ESF</li><li>The distribution of the ESF to public schools should be on a per capita basis and all school heads should be given the opportunity to identify their priority targets</li><li>Municipal government-owned lots used as school sites should be transferred to the Department of Education</li><li>Coordinate with the Technical Education and Skills Development Authority (TESDA) and the Commission on Higher Education (CHED) for the immediate establishment of such institutions</li><li>Promotion of Primary Health Care</li><li>Greater Emphasis on Promotive and Preventive Health Care</li><li>Strict Implementation of Existing Ordinances on Solid Waste Management</li><li>Increased Budgetary Allocation for the Purchase of Medicine and Medical Supplies</li><li>Sourcing of funding support for day care centers</li><li>Allocation of funds for livelihood and income generating projects</li><li>Intensification of the nutrition program thru massive supplemental feeding to malnourished children</li><li>Coordination with TESDA TLRC for skills development training for youth and&nbsp; mothers</li><li>Identification and listing of potential clients and community leaders</li><li>Activation and strengthening of existing organizations for disaster management and preparedness</li><li>Strengthening of the participation of NGOs to promote and implement programs through linkages and proper coordination</li><li>Training and mobilization of community volunteers and organization of the welfare structure</li><li>Putting up of Day Care Centers</li><li>Organization of an Out of School Youth (OSY) Groups</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->', 'GOALS, OBJECTIVES, STRATEGIES', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '106-revision-v1', '', '', '2020-09-14 07:06:16', '2020-09-14 07:06:16', '', 106, 'https://localhost/git/burgos-website/?p=190', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(191, 1, '2020-09-14 07:07:38', '2020-09-14 07:07:38', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The municipality has adopted the following goals, objectives and strategies:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>1.GOALS</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul style=\"list-style-type:none;\"><li><strong>1.1. Agriculture</strong><br><br>\n<ul><li>To supervise poverty alleviation and social equity</li><li>To intensify food production</li><li>To attain food sufficiency</li><li>To achieve rational use of agricultural resources</li><li>To achieve sustainable development</li><li>To support people empowerment</li></ul></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul style=\"list-style-type:none;\"><li><strong>1.2. Commerce and Industry</strong><br><br>\n<ul><li>To increase municipal income through increased commercial and industrial activity</li><li>To expand commercial activity outside of the Poblacion</li><li>To minimize the municipal poverty rate through economic uplifting of the populace through commercial and industrial support</li></ul></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>1.3. Infrastructure and Tourism</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>To improve the existing urban and rural roads of the municipality</li><li>To improve the farm to market roads in every barangay in order to spur economic development in the rural areas</li><li>To attain the safe and efficient movement of people, goods, services and information needed for municipal wide development</li><li>To provide the municipality with adequate and safe supply of water suitable for domestic consumption, water impounding and irrigation</li><li>To expand the Level II and construct a Level III Municipal Waterworks System</li><li>To energize the local economy through the modernization and expansion of the present water facilities</li><li>To provide the municipality’s population with adequate power supply to increase prof